  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Okay, let's break down the penalties for money laundering under federal law in the United States.  Keep in mind that this is a general overview and specific circumstances can significantly affect the actual penalties imposed.  It's always best to consult with a qualified legal professional for advice on any specific situation.\n\n**Key Federal Laws**\n\nThe main federal laws dealing with money laundering are:\n\n*   **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of Monetary Instruments):** This is the core money laundering statute.\n*   **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in Monetary Transactions in Property Derived from Specified Unlawful Activity):** This statute targets spending illicit funds.\n\n**18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of Monetary Instruments)**\n\nThis statute prohibits a wide range of activities related to concealing or disguising the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of illegally obtained funds.  It has two main subsections, (a)(1) and (a)(2), each with different intent requirements:\n\n*   **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956(a)(1):** This section targets those who conduct financial transactions knowing that the property involved represents the proceeds of some form of unlawful activity *and* with the **intent** to:\n    *   Promote the carrying on of specified unlawful activity; *or*\n    *   Conceal or disguise the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of the proceeds of specified unlawful activity; *or*\n    *   Avoid a transaction reporting requirement under state or federal law.\n\n    *   **Penalties:**\n        *   **Maximum 20 years in prison.**\n        *   **A fine of $500,000 or twice the amount of money laundered, whichever is greater.** (This \"twice the amount\" provision can lead to very substantial fines).\n        *   Both imprisonment and a fine can be imposed.\n        *   Forfeiture of any property involved in the offense (or traceable to such property).\n\n*   **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956(a)(2):** This section targets those who transport, transmit, or transfer monetary instruments or funds into or out of the United States knowing that the funds represent the proceeds of some form of unlawful activity *and* with the **intent** to:\n    ",
